Oct 12 2009 	A total and utter failure on value service location - stay away	I stayed in two hotels whilst in San Francisco, this was the more expensive of the two by a factor of twice the price, and yet it was a total disgrace. I have not had a worse hotel experience and would never stay in this hotel again.It took 15 minutes to check in at 7pm with two staff on reception and no apology for the wait. Once in the room on the 9th floor, I discover the WiFi requires you to call back to reception for the password. But trying to call reception was impossible as they have an automated menu that does everything possible to dissuade you from talking to a human being. Once I finally got it to ring through to the front desk, it rang solidly for 10 minutes with no answer. Eventually it was answered but with the comment &quot;Putting you on hold, one moment&quot; and I was then on hold for a further ten minutes, at which point someone else entirely answered, sounded indignant to my call and gave me the code with a tone that suggested I had inconvenienced then, with no apology for the wait. It took over half an hour to check in and connect to WiFi and all in vain as the WiFi was so flaky it was barely worth using. Things shouldn't have to be this difficult or sub-standard.The room itself was standard chain hotel fare, but very cold and for the price it was a little tatty with stains on the carpet and a very dirty and unpleasant looking non-slip surface to the bath. Certainly way way below the standard accepted in the UK for hotels in this price range. You'd think appalling check in, useless WiFi and a very tired looking room would be bad enough for a price approaching $200 - but this is just the beginning.Both that evening and on the morning of check out I saw adults openly defecating in the street nearby - a man in the evening and a woman in the morning. Clearly crack addicts, and I am streetwise enough that this thing does not scare or surprise me, but any hotel in the Tenderloin needs to work extra hard to justify their pricing and Holiday Inn totally fail to do so. Clearly I'm not getting value on the horrible location (and I would warn against more sensitive people staying in this neighbourhood) so I expected the value to be in the accomodation and service, which of course, it absolutely wasn't.On the morning of a Sunday check out I had pushy housekeeping who woke me up by banging open my door in an apparent &quot;hurry up&quot; gesture twice well before the supposed check out time of noon, which is unforgivable on a Sunday morning. Then when I went to check out they presented me with a $300 bill which included dinner in their restaurant. I don't even know where their restaurant is so it is extremely worrying how things can just appear in this way, at worst dishonest, at best hugely incompetent administration. As this was all being pre-authorised to my debit card I dread to think what funds were reserved.To cap it all, I asked them to phone a taxi for me (and bear in mind I have been polite and courteous throughout my stay and not complained to the staff themselves, so would not expect them to have any reason to discriminate against me in their service) but even this simple request was too much, instead of phoning they sent the porter outside to flag one and I followed, but immediately outside he said &quot;you won't get a taxi here&quot; (the hotel is 50 yards off the main street) and told me to go up to the main street and flag one for myself. I had two large heavy bags so had to haul them up there and go it alone trying to get one, which defeats the whole point of asking for their help. It took 45 minutes as the doorman of another hotel up on the main street was flagging them or calling them on a mobile for his hotels guests, which proves that some people have an idea about service.The hotel was utterly abysmal in every respect, and I would be embarrassed to work for this hotel and will never use this chain again. Holiday Inn San Francisco Civic Centre is appalling and should be avoided at all costs. The other hotel I stayed at in SF was the Metro Hotel in Lower Haight which was half the price, well run, in a safe neighbourhood, with fast Wi-Fi, clean rooms, helpful housekeeping, courteous staff (who did ring a taxi for me) and everything that the Holiday Inn Civic Centre was not. I wouldn't stay at the Civic Centre Holiday Inn if it was half the price, please don't make the mistake of staying there at the prices they actually have the nerve to charge!	
